abstract: MORRISTOWN, N.J., Aug. 5. -- Morris Lodge, I.O.O.F., of this city, held its annual excursion at Rockaway Beach, L.I., last Wednesday. It was in charge of a committee consisting of Mayor Quayle, George W. Bowers, Mancing Youmans, Augustus Paul, and Frank Person. abstract: Greece is, undoubtedly, the most democratic nation in Europe -- perhaps in the world. In Southeastern Europe the rule of the Turk obliterated all social distinctions, and swept away every vestige of feudalism. Roumania alone, which was never so completely under the Turkish yoke, retains an aristocratic class; but Servia, Bulgaria, and Greece are democratic to the core.

abstract: Ovid's "Metamorphoses," and in a less degree his "Fasti," are valuable not only as story books and poems, but as documents for the history of ideas. Ovid was a collector of traditions on a vast scale. He had an incomparable knowledge of legends, prejudices, customs, rites, and if he embellished more than the Folklore Society would strictly approve, there is reason to think that he never invented.

abstract: Last week was an exciting one in Stock Exchange circles. Monday was a comparatively quiet day, with a small recession in in prices, but on Tuesday stocks broke badly on the announcement of the Moore Brothers' failure, and the consequent indefinite closing of the Chicago Stock Exchange. Liquidation of investment holdings continued throughout the week, and was most pronounced on Friday and Saturday.

abstract: PORT HURON, Mich., Aug. 9. -- Edward Henkel, aged forty-three, son and successor of Peter Henkel, proprietor of the largest and oldest wholesale grocery and liquor house in Detroit, was killed here to-day on his yacht, the Azalea. abstract: WASHINGTON, Aug. 9. -- The heated term that has been almost without precedent in this city continues, and the general impression is that to-day has been beyond all doubt the hottest and most uncomfortable of the season. The churches were comparatively very sparsely attended, the streets almost deserted, and many people left the city in the early morning for river resorts and suburban retreats, in the hope of escaping the torrid temperature of the city.

abstract: Novelists as a class, already take themselves too seriously. Atlas holding up the word is only a figure symbolic of the novelist's conception of his own place in the scheme of the universe of to-day. To the novelist the novel is identical with modern thought; that is, it is the only adequate vehicle of expression for all the moods, brood-tugs, hopes, aspirations, grapings, philosophies, and what not of modern life.

abstract: When Vuillaume came upon the "Salabue" Stradivarius he went into raptures over it. Indeed, such was his enthusiasm that he refused to part with the instrument at any price; and when the Franco-German war was going on in 1870 he had the treasure buried in damp-proof, airtight box for safety. Vuillaume went the way of all flesh, and then the violin passed into the hands of M. Alard, who gave 1,000 for it.

abstract: Cloaked and turbaned, they glide bout in slippered feet, the women shod in red, the men in bright yellow. But for their exceedingly substantial build the Moorish women in the street might pass for ghosts, for their costume is, with this one exception, white. A long and heavy blanket of coarse homespun effectually conceals every feature but the eyes, which are touched up with antimony on the lids, and as a rule are sufficiently expressive.

abstract: Macaulay's theory, that with the advance of civilization poetry must inevitably decline, is not quite true; he should have said that it changes its character, but this is because poetry has life for its subject matter. abstract: One of the queerest reunions in the history of Indiana will take place at Auburn, De Kalb County, on Aug. 20. It is to be composed of the men and women who have been united in marriage by the Rev. W.L. Meese during his ministry there. They form a fair proportion of the population of De Kalb County, besides being represented in every other State in the Union.

abstract: Mr. Drudenelle Carter made arrangements with the authories of twenty-five commentary schools in London, with the result that 8,125 children were subjected to simple tests of vision. Of these it turned out that just under 40 per cent, were possessed of normal vision in Loth eye. abstract: Slavery in its legal form was extinguished at Cape Town about the year 1834. The English Government, which had at that time taken over Cape Colony, purchased and liberated all the slaves, at a cost of 1,247,000. Officially slavery passed away; but it left, as always, its indelible marks on the dominant race who had suffered from it.

abstract: The rule that the whole is equal to the sum of all its parts has a curious exception in a big public audience. abstract: -- The crew of the bark William Geake, which was wrecked at Biron's Island, in the Gulf of St. Lawrence, Aug. 2, have arrived at Halifax, N.S. The Geake encountered a gale July 31, was dismasted, and rendered helpless. She struck the rocks, and the crew took to the boats. The bark went to pieces, and nothing was saved. She had a full cargo of molasses from Barbados for Montreal, where the vessel was owned.

abstract: The rain caused a postponement of the Atalanta Wheelmen's race meet at Waverly Park yesterday afternoon. Fully fifty racing men, unable to ascertain beforehand that the meet would not be held, gathered about the entrance to the park shortly before 1 o'clock and patiently waited in the drizzle for the gates to open. The club had no representative present, and after a wait of over an hour an indignation meeting was held.

abstract: HAVANA, Aug. 27. -- The report of an engagement between insurgents and Spanish troops near Manzanillo has been received here. The Spanish force, which was commanded by Capt. abstract: NEWPORT, R.I., Aug. 29. -- The thirty-footers sailed to-day for a cup given by Bayard Thayer of Boston, owner of the Asahi. abstract: SCHENECTADY, N.Y., Aug. 29. -- Dennis W. Collins of the livery firm of Collins  Boyd of Amsterdam has received a letter announcing that the body of his brother, John Collins, has been found in the North wood, fifteen miles beyond Lake Piseco.
